<subSubSection id="C321D5CAF17FFFEF2E98FBEEFD39D0AF" lastPageId="18" lastPageNumber="181" pageId="17" pageNumber="180" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8B848641F17FFFEF2E98FBEEFD39D0AF" lastPageId="18" lastPageNumber="181" pageId="17" pageNumber="180">
Comments: This ♀ cannot be reliably identified or described as a new species. On the basis of its copulatory organs (
<figureCitation id="13009AC4F17FFFEC2C24FB8DFDC6D51B" box="[521,603,1089,1116]" captionStart="Figs 70 – 72" captionStartId="17.[181,221,1628,1650]" captionTargetBox="[196,1133,1193,1603]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[187,1147,1186,1607]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="Figs 70 – 72. Meleon sp. from Uganda, female: (70) epigyne, ventral view; (71) spermathecae, dorsal view; (72) ditto, dorsolateral view. Scale bars: 0.1 mm." pageId="17" pageNumber="180">
Fig. 
<number id="3DF39466F17FFFEC2C10FB8DFDC6D51B" box="[573,603,1089,1116]" pageId="17" pageNumber="180" value="70.0">70</number>
</figureCitation>
), it is most close to, but clearly distinct from, 
<taxonomicName id="4C3BFDC2F17FFFEC2A7AFB8FFDABD53B" authority="Wijesinghe 1994" authorityName="Wijesinghe" authorityYear="1994" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Meleon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="17" pageNumber="180" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="solitaria">
<emphasis id="B94F5A53F17FFFEC2A7AFB8FFE89D53B" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="180">M. solitaria</emphasis>
(
<emphasis id="B94F5A53F17FFFEC2F08FBAFFEFED53B" box="[293,355,1123,1148]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="180">sensu</emphasis>
Wijesinghe 
<number id="3DF39466F17FFFEC2FDCFBADFDB0D53B" box="[497,557,1121,1148]" pageId="17" pageNumber="180" value="1994.0">1994</number>
)
</taxonomicName>
. It can be easily distinguished from the ♀ 
<typeStatus id="548038E3F17FFFEC2A3EFBADFBE8D53B" box="[1043,1141,1121,1148]" pageId="17" pageNumber="180">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<emphasis id="B94F5A53F17CFFEF2E83FF02FEB4D1AF" box="[174,297,205,232]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="181">
<taxonomicName id="4C3BFDC2F17CFFEF2E83FF02FEB4D1AF" box="[174,297,205,232]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Meleon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="18" pageNumber="181" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="solitaria">P. solitaria</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
by the ovoid shape of the spermathecae (cf. 
<figureCitation id="13009AC4F17CFFEF2D0CFF01FC02D1AF" box="[801,927,205,232]" captionStart="Figs 70 – 72" captionStartId="17.[181,221,1628,1650]" captionTargetBox="[196,1133,1193,1603]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[187,1147,1186,1607]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="Figs 70 – 72. Meleon sp. from Uganda, female: (70) epigyne, ventral view; (71) spermathecae, dorsal view; (72) ditto, dorsolateral view. Scale bars: 0.1 mm." pageId="18" pageNumber="181">Figs 71, 72</figureCitation>
and figs 
<quantity id="4CC32BA4F17CFFEF2A2BFF02FBCDD1AF" box="[1030,1104,205,232]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.27" metricValueMax="1.524" metricValueMin="1.016" pageId="18" pageNumber="181" unit="in" value="5.0" valueMax="6.0" valueMin="4.0">4–6 in</quantity>
Wijesinghe 
<number id="3DF39466F17CFFEF2F38FF21FECCD04F" box="[277,337,237,264]" pageId="18" pageNumber="181" value="1994.0">1994</number>
). However, the current conception of the latter species is based on the assumption that the ♀ 
<typeStatus id="548038E3F17CFFEF2FBFFEC1FE69D06F" box="[402,500,269,296]" pageId="18" pageNumber="181">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<emphasis id="B94F5A53F17CFFEF2C31FEC2FD56D06F" box="[540,715,269,296]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="181">
<taxonomicName id="4C3BFDC2F17CFFEF2C31FEC2FD56D06F" box="[540,715,269,296]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Portia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="18" pageNumber="181" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="solitaria">Portia solitaria</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
from Zaire and the ♂ 
<typeStatus id="548038E3F17CFFEF2DE3FEC1FBADD06F" box="[974,1072,269,296]" pageId="18" pageNumber="181">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName id="4C3BFDC2F17CFFEF2EBDFEE2FE40D00F" authority="Wanless, 1978" authorityName="Wanless" authorityYear="1978" box="[144,477,301,328]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Portia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="18" pageNumber="181" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="falsifera">
<emphasis id="B94F5A53F17CFFEF2EBDFEE2FEA5D00F" box="[144,312,301,328]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="181">Portia falsifera</emphasis>
Wanless, 
<number id="3DF39466F17CFFEF2F88FEE2FE40D00F" box="[421,477,302,328]" pageId="18" pageNumber="181" value="1978.0">1978</number>
</taxonomicName>
from Uganda belong to the same species (see Wijesinghe 
<number id="3DF39466F17CFFEF2EBDFE82FF51D02F" box="[144,204,334,360]" pageId="18" pageNumber="181" value="1994.0">1994</number>
: 
<number id="3DF39466F17CFFEF2EF8FE81FF68D02F" box="[213,245,333,360]" pageId="18" pageNumber="181" value="60.0">60</number>
). On the contrary, it is very likely that our ♀ from Uganda and the ♂ 
<typeStatus id="548038E3F17CFFEF2DC3FE81FBCDD02F" box="[1006,1104,333,360]" pageId="18" pageNumber="181">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<emphasis id="B94F5A53F17CFFEF2E80FEA2FEB8D0CF" box="[173,293,365,392]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="181">
<taxonomicName id="4C3BFDC2F17CFFEF2E80FEA2FEB8D0CF" box="[173,293,365,392]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Portia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="18" pageNumber="181" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="falsifera">P. falsifera</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
belong to the same taxon. If so, the latter name should be revalidated and removed from the synonymy with 
<emphasis id="B94F5A53F17CFFEF2C35FE42FD03D0EF" box="[536,670,397,424]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="181">
<taxonomicName id="4C3BFDC2F17CFFEF2C35FE42FD03D0EF" box="[536,670,397,424]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Portia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="18" pageNumber="181" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="solitaria">M. solitaria</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
. Thus, the studied ♀ belongs either to 
<emphasis id="B94F5A53F17CFFEF2EBDFE62FE8ED08F" box="[144,275,429,456]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="181">
<taxonomicName id="4C3BFDC2F17CFFEF2EBDFE62FE8ED08F" box="[144,275,429,456]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Portia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="18" pageNumber="181" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="falsifera">M. falsifera</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
or to a new species. The matter can be finally decided when a sample of 
<emphasis id="B94F5A53F17CFFEF2EBDFE02FE8FD0AF" box="[144,274,461,488]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="181">
<taxonomicName id="4C3BFDC2F17CFFEF2EBDFE02FE8FD0AF" box="[144,274,461,488]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Portia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="18" pageNumber="181" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="falsifera">M. falsifera</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
with both sexes has been collected.
</paragraph>
